# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen-city-council
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1884-aberdeen-corporation-election] This election was the first time labour-affiliated candidates won seats in Aberdeen's municipal elections.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1884-aberdeen-corporation-election] The candidates, James Forbes and George Maconnachie, were supported by the Aberdeen United Trades Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1884-aberdeen-corporation-election] The primary question at hand was the rates of councillors' salaries, and public feelings on the matter were clear as all retiring councillors but one were not re-elected.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1885-aberdeen-corporation-election] This election marked a conversion of sitting councillors to a labour programme.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1885-aberdeen-corporation-election] John Morgan of Greyfriars, who was elected temporarily after a councillor resigned, stood affiliated with the Aberdeen United Trades Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1885-aberdeen-corporation-election] The same situation occurred with Alexander Lyon Jr. of St.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1885-aberdeen-corporation-election] Nicholas, who had lost to a Trades Council candidate at the previous election.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1885-aberdeen-corporation-election] All three seats in Greyfriars ward were up for election as two councillors resigned and one was disqualified from holding office.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1907-aberdeen-corporation-election] This election saw the first municipal contests in Aberdeen with a candidate supported by the Aberdeen Labour Representation Committee (LRC).
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1907-aberdeen-corporation-election] While unaffiliated with the national body that had formed in 1900, this local group was modeled and named the same.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1907-aberdeen-corporation-election] The LRC consisted of the Aberdeen United Trades Council, the local branches of the Social Democratic Federation and the Independent Labour Party, and the Working Women's Political Association, a local women's suffrage group which later folded into a branch of the Women's Social and Political Union.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1907-aberdeen-corporation-election] The group was originally formed to contest the 1907 Aberdeen South by-election.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1908-aberdeen-corporation-election] The primary question in this election was the 'Water Question,' a debate of whether the city should continue to obtain drinking water from the River Dee, or if a new supply should be pulled from River Avon.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1908-aberdeen-corporation-election] Many reports had been commissioned over the years, the most recent one from Alexander Binnie and George Deacon in October 1908, which had recommended a new water intake to be constructed on the Avon near the settlement of Inchrory.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1908-aberdeen-corporation-election] Issues had been raised over pollutants coming from villages upstream of Aberdeen on the Dee, resulting in some favouring another river, while others felt attached to the Dee, desiring funding to be put towards filtration of the present system.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1908-aberdeen-corporation-election] All three Labour candidates supported the Avon scheme, while all three independents supported continuing to use the Dee.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] This election continued the 'Water Question,' debating whether the town's drinking water supply should be pulled from the River Dee or the River Avon.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] On 15 September 1909, the corporation had voted 19 to 13 to approve pursuing a local act in order to fund the Avon water scheme.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] Despite this, many considered the matter still open, and John G.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] Scott of Woodside stood specifically for this matter, winning against a councillor that supported the Avon in September.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] In Greyfriars, Councillor Alexander Duncan voted for the Dee previously and won by a large margin.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] Andrew's both candidates effectively supported the Dee, Chalmers stating he was no longer convinced of the Avon scheme, a change from last election.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1909-aberdeen-corporation-election] Although James George of Torry was labeled as a socialist in local papers, he was not backed by the local Labour Party, but was rather just a member of a trade union.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1949-aberdeen-corporation-election] The election saw Labour retain their control over the corporation, although tenuously.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1949-aberdeen-corporation-election] Leading up to the election, Labour councillor Robert S.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1949-aberdeen-corporation-election] Lennox had the whip withdrawn, and was sitting as an independent.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1949-aberdeen-corporation-election] Despite this, Lennox still voted with Labour, allowing the party to keep control.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1949-aberdeen-corporation-election] The overall turnout for the election was 46%.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1950-aberdeen-corporation-election] The election saw the Progressives regain one seat from Labour in the Gilcomston Ward and hold a one-seat majority on the council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/1950-aberdeen-corporation-election] The overall turnout for the election was 39.4%.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-city-council/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
